  "drug_name": "Pyloric_stenosis",
  "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Pyloric_stenosis",
  "scraped_at": "2026-01-10T08:01:01.642175",
  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "More common in males (5:1) & firstborn children (30%)\nPrematurity and macrolide use are also thought to be risk factors\nMost common surgical cause of vomiting in infants\nThe main diagnostic criterion is a measurement of more than 3 mm in thickness of the muscular layer on ultrasound.\n[1]\nAbnormal elongation of the canal is characterised as greater than 17 mm in length .\n[2]\n[3]",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Symptoms usually begin between 3-6 weeks of age, rarely after 12 weeks\nVomiting\n, immediately postprandial, nonbilious, often projectile, but desires to feed (\"hungry vomiter\")\nPalpable mass in in RUQ to epigastric region after vomiting, occasionally may see reverse peristaltic fluid wave across abdomen\nIf untreated, will see signs of\ndehydration\n, weight loss,\nlethargy\n,\nshock",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
